SIMPLE: hoodoo
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hoodoo
<hw>Hoo"doo</hw> <pr>(h⟦oomac⟧"d⟦oomac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh.
a var. of <ets>voodoo</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who causes bad
luck.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>voodoo</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Bad luck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoodoo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hoodoo
<hw>Hoo"doo</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To be a hoodoo to; to bring bad
luck to by occult influence; to bewitch.</def> <mark>[Colloq., U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoodoo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hoodoo
<hw>Hoo"doo</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A natural rock pile or pinnacle of
fantastic shape.</def> <mark>[Western U. S.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧I watched for
hours as the shadows moved through the <xex>hoodoos</xex> in Bryce
Canyon park.⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hoodooism</ent>⟦br⟧
